{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7dda0b9e-279c-46cb-b8d6-7d0545b2f261","content":"Here's the migration mapping:\n\n| VSTest flag | Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalent | Required NuGet package |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--treenode-filter \"/**/*[Tag=Integration]\"` | *(built-in)* |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**New command** (arguments after `--` are forwarded to the platform):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/*[Tag=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key things to do in your test project:**\n\n1. Add the four NuGet packages listed above.\n2. Enable the new platform in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>   <!-- if MSTest -->\n   <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n   <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   ```\n3. The `[TestCategory(\"Integration\")]` attribute maps to `Tag=Integration` in tree-node filter syntax — verify with `--list-tests` after migrating.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6587b63c-eea4-45a4-a380-2b2c0b5af009","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure - I can answer this directly.\n\nLet me break down their current command and map each part:\n\nCurrent command:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" --logger trx --collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\" --blame-crash --blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m\n```\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the CLI changes significantly. The key differences:\n\n1. `dotnet test` still works but the arguments change when using Microsoft.Testing.Platform\n\n\n2. The filter syntax stays the same, but the logging and collection options shift - `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` (requiring the TrxReport extension package), and code coverage switches to `--coverage` with `--coverage-output-format cobertura` when using Microsoft.CodeCoverage\n3. The blame options like `--crashdump` replace `--blame-crash`, though some of these features may need additional extension packages to work with the new testing platform\n4. When using `dotnet test` versus running the test executable directly, the command-line interface differs slightly - `dotnet test` now acts as an orchestrator, and while `--filter` remains compatible, there's also a newer `--treenode-filter` syntax available, plus `--report-trx` handles TRX output (with the TrxReport package), `--coverage` with format options handles code coverage (CodeCoverage package), and `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` with timeout settings handle diagnostic dumps respectively. The key distinction is that in .NET 8 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the test project becomes an executable, so I can either run it directly or through `dotnet test`, though .NET 9+ provides better integration where `dotnet test` forwards arguments more seamlessly to the platform. Finishing the filter syntax and command structure...\n\nFor .NET 8 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I need to add the specific NuGet packages for TRX reporting, code coverage, crash dumps, and hang dumps. Then the command uses `--treenode-filter` with the pattern `\"/**/Category=Integration\"` to filter tests, followed by the reporting and diagnostic flags.","outputTokens":1681,"requestId":"E3C9:3BB7E3:1ADB33F:1DD4891:6A05200E"},"id":"9810ae6a-0aaa-4c54-b3da-997129b2d424","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:06:49.518Z","parentId":"5c715393-f195-4878-b168-9c512cf06c23"}
